"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Deuteronomy chapters 14–17
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-deuteronomy-14-17-fill.py

Key decisions:
- Ch 14: dietary laws treated as shadow; Acts 10 Peter's vision as the fulfillment transition
- Ch 14 v21: "goat in its mother's milk" prohibition treated thematically (life-perverted-to-death pattern)
- Ch 15 v11: Jesus quotes directly in Matt 26:11 — noted as direct citation
- Ch 15 vv.16-17: ear-piercing of the willing slave = type of Christ's Incarnation (Heb 10:5-7 citing Ps 40)
- Ch 15 vv.19-21: firstborn consecration = type of Christ as firstborn (Col 1:15, 18; Rom 8:29)
- Ch 16: Three feasts read Christologically — Passover (death), Weeks/Pentecost (Spirit), Booths (tabernacling)
- Ch 16 v9-10: Feast of Weeks = Pentecost; Spirit poured out on the firstfruits grain feast
- Ch 17 vv.14-20: law of the king = direct type of the Davidic messianic king fulfilled in Christ
- Ch 17 v12: Heb 10:28-29 explicitly applies Deut 17:12 logic to Christ's superior authority
- Directness levels: direct (NT explicit), type, shadow, theme, revelation of God
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DEUTERONOMY = {
"14": {
"1": "<p>&quot;You are the children of the LORD your God.&quot; Identity precedes obligation — sonship is established before any prohibition is addressed. The dietary and mourning laws that follow are grounded in who Israel already is, not in what they must do to become acceptable. The NT develops this sequence explicitly in Galatians 4:4–6: &quot;God sent his Son... so that we might receive adoption as sons. And because you are sons, God has sent the Spirit of his Son into our hearts.&quot; In Christ, the sonship announced to Israel is extended to all who are united to him. Theme.</p>",
"2": "<p>&quot;You are a people holy to the LORD your God, and the LORD has chosen you to be his treasured possession.&quot; The double identity: qāḏôš (holy) and sĕgullâ (treasured possession). Peter applies both directly to the church in Christ: &quot;you are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, a people for his own possession&quot; (1 Pet 2:9 — the same ʿam sĕgullâ language). The election-identity of Israel becomes the election-identity of the church through union with Christ. Direct connection.</p>",
"3": "<p>&quot;You shall not eat any detestable thing.&quot; The prohibition of what is toʿēḇâ — an abomination — marks the boundary of covenant identity. The dietary laws as a whole create a visible distinction between Israel and the surrounding nations. As a shadow: the physical distinctions that maintained Israel&apos;s separation from the nations are superseded when Christ&apos;s mission expands to all nations. Acts 10:15 — &quot;What God has made clean, do not call common&quot; — is the declaration that the separating wall has served its purpose. Shadow.</p>",
"4": "<p>Clean land animals permitted: ox, sheep, and goat — the primary domestic livestock, the animals of the covenant sacrificial system. The clean animals are precisely those used in Israel&apos;s offerings. As a revelation of God&apos;s design: the animals that sustain daily life and the animals that serve covenant worship overlap — the sacred and the everyday are not compartmentalized. In Christ, this integration is complete: &quot;whether you eat or drink, or whatever you do, do all to the glory of God&quot; (1 Cor 10:31). Revelation of God.</p>",
"5": "<p>Wild game permitted: deer, gazelle, roe deer, wild goat, ibex, antelope, mountain sheep. The extension of clean status to wild animals not used in the sacrificial system — edible food is not limited to the sanctuary&apos;s animals. The goodness of creation extends beyond the cultic system. In Christ, the goodness of all creation is affirmed (1 Tim 4:4 — &quot;everything created by God is good, and nothing is to be rejected if it is received with thanksgiving&quot;). Revelation of God.</p>",
"6": "<p>The two identifying marks of clean land animals: completely split hooves and chewing the cud. The visible taxonomy creates a system of distinction perceivable to any observer. The physical markers of cleanness point toward the inner transformation the covenant truly requires — a correspondence between the visible and the real. What the external law can only mark visibly, Christ produces inwardly: the Spirit-transformed heart that matches the outer confession (Rom 2:29; 2 Cor 3:3). Theme.</p>",
"7": "<p>Animals that chew the cud but lack split hooves (camel, hare, rock badger) are unclean — one mark is not enough; both are required. The strictness of the double-criterion points to the completeness of what God requires. The clean animal must fully satisfy both conditions. Christ fully satisfies every covenantal requirement without partial compliance — &quot;he fulfilled all righteousness&quot; (Matt 3:15) and &quot;has done everything well&quot; (Mark 7:37). Theme.</p>",
"8": "<p>The pig — split hooves but does not chew the cud — is the paradigmatic unclean animal. Jesus uses pig-related imagery in the parable of the Prodigal Son (Luke 15:15–16): the son&apos;s lowest degradation is feeding pigs, longing for their food. The pig represents both ritual uncleanness and creaturely existence at its most debased. The Father&apos;s reception of the son who was among pigs is the gospel of radical restoration: no level of uncleanness places a person beyond the Father&apos;s embrace. Theme.</p>",
"9": "<p>Water creatures with fins and scales are clean. The visible structures of the fish — fins to move, scales to protect — are the markers of ordered, purposeful life. As a theme of God&apos;s design: the Creator marks out what sustains life and what does not. In Christ, the Creator who designed the distinctions between clean and unclean comes in person — &quot;the Word through whom all things were made&quot; (John 1:3) is the same one who transcends these distinctions in himself, declaring all foods clean (Mark 7:18–19). Revelation of God.</p>",
"10": "<p>Whatever lacks fins or scales is unclean. The principle: the absence of the ordering structures makes the creature unusable for the covenant community. As a shadow: the clean/unclean system prepares for the day when Christ, by his atonement, removes the barrier of uncleanness and makes all peoples accessible to the covenant community. &quot;What God has made clean, do not call common&quot; (Acts 10:15) — the vision that ends the dietary separation is the vision that opens the Gentile mission. Shadow.</p>",
"11": "<p>&quot;You may eat any clean bird.&quot; The general permission for clean birds. The Deuteronomic code assumes the daily life of God&apos;s people — eating is a covenantal act. In Christ, all eating becomes eucharistic in principle: &quot;So whether you eat or drink, or whatever you do, do all to the glory of God&quot; (1 Cor 10:31). The clean-bird permission is one facet of the covenant structure that integrates worship and daily life. Revelation of God.</p>",
"12": "<p>The eagle, bearded vulture, and black vulture are unclean — birds of prey and carrion. These birds are associated with death (scavenging carcasses) and violence (predation). The unclean birds are those most associated with death and carrion. In Christ, death itself is defeated: the birds that feed on the dead are denied their feast because the one they would feed on rises. Revelation 19:17–21, which describes birds feasting on the carcasses of God&apos;s enemies at the final judgment, is the eschatological inversion. Theme.</p>",
"13": "<p>Kite and every kind of falcon — unclean birds of prey. The list continues with birds of prey. As a theme: the prohibition on birds that take life by force reflects the covenant community&apos;s alignment with the God of life rather than of predatory violence. Jesus&apos; instructions to his disciples inverse the predatory-force model: &quot;I am sending you out as sheep in the midst of wolves&quot; (Matt 10:16) — the covenant community embodies non-predatory vulnerability, trusting the God of life. Theme.</p>",
"14": "<p>Every kind of raven — unclean. The raven is significant in the OT: Noah sends the raven first (Gen 8:7); ravens feed Elijah at the Wadi Cherith (1 Kgs 17:4). Even the unclean raven is fed by God and used by God as a servant. Jesus uses ravens to illustrate God&apos;s providential care: &quot;Consider the ravens: they neither sow nor reap... yet God feeds them. Of how much more value are you than the birds!&quot; (Luke 12:24). The raven, though ritually unclean, testifies to the Father&apos;s universal providence. Theme.</p>",
"15": "<p>Ostrich, nighthawk, sea gull, hawk — unclean birds. The list moves through the spectrum of birds associated with the wilderness, night, and sea. As a revelation of God&apos;s order: every creature exists within a system the Creator designed. The unclean animals are not chaotic but ordered — placed in their categories by the same wisdom that orders all creation. In Christ, &quot;the wisdom of God&quot; (1 Cor 1:24) is the creative ordering principle made visible. Revelation of God.</p>",
"16": "<p>Little owl, screech owl, barn owl — unclean. Owls are nocturnal, associated with the dark. The light-dark contrast runs through biblical theology: YHWH creates light and separates it from darkness (Gen 1:3–4). In Christ: &quot;I am the light of the world. Whoever follows me will not walk in darkness, but will have the light of life&quot; (John 8:12). The creatures of darkness are unclean; the people of the covenant belong to the light. Theme.</p>",
"17": "<p>Pelican, carrion vulture, cormorant — unclean. These are water birds associated with death-feeding or fish-taking. Even in this administrative list of prohibited birds, the underlying principle is the Creator&apos;s ordering of creation — the covenant people eat within a designed system that reflects the wisdom of their God. All such ordering finds its source in the Word through whom all things were created (John 1:3; Col 1:16). Revelation of God.</p>",
"18": "<p>Stork, heron, hoopoe, bat — unclean. The bat is technically a mammal but is grouped with the birds. The list covers the full range of flying creatures associated with scavenging, night, and wetlands. As a broader theme: the clean/unclean system in its entirety anticipates the day when Christ declares the system fulfilled and the mission expands to all peoples. &quot;What God has made clean, do not call common&quot; (Acts 10:15) — the list of unclean birds is overturned in the declaration that opens the Gentile mission. Shadow.</p>",
"19": "<p>All winged insects are unclean — they shall not be eaten. The general prohibition covers the final category of flying creatures. (Leviticus 11:20–23 provides the exception for locusts, which John the Baptist eats — Mark 1:6. The prophetic figure in the wilderness lives by the boundary-edge of the law.) As a theme: the comprehensive taxonomic system prepares for the comprehensive fulfillment in Christ, who cleanses not a category at a time but the whole order by his atoning work. Theme.</p>",
"20": "<p>&quot;But all clean birds you may eat.&quot; The permissive summary. The covenant God is a God of permission and provision, not only prohibition. The gifts of creation are for the enjoyment of the covenant community. In Christ, the goodness of creation is affirmed and extended: &quot;everything created by God is good, and nothing is to be rejected if it is received with thanksgiving, for it is made holy by the word of God and prayer&quot; (1 Tim 4:4–5). Revelation of God.</p>",
"21": "<p>Israel shall not eat anything that dies of itself; the prohibition closes with: &quot;You shall not boil a young goat in its mother&apos;s milk.&quot; The life-perverting prohibition: the milk designed to nourish and sustain the kid must not become the medium of its death. The principle: God&apos;s life-giving provisions must not be perverted into instruments of death. In Christ, the perversion of life-giving creation is reversed — what was given for life but became the instrument of death (the covenant law itself, through human sin) is now restored to its life-giving purpose (Rom 7:10–12; 8:1–4). Theme.</p>",
"22": "<p>&quot;You shall tithe all the yield of your seed that comes from the field each year.&quot; The tithe as the systematic acknowledgment that every harvest belongs to YHWH — the first tenth is the representative portion that consecrates the whole. In Christ, the principle of first-fruits offering is fulfilled and reframed: &quot;Each one must give as he has decided in his heart, not reluctantly or under compulsion, for God loves a cheerful giver&quot; (2 Cor 9:7). The tithe becomes freewill generosity; the form changes, the principle — all belongs to God — remains. Theme.</p>",
"23": "<p>Eat the tithe before the LORD at the central sanctuary &quot;so that you may learn to fear the LORD your God always.&quot; The tithe feast before YHWH is a formative covenant meal — eating in God&apos;s presence cultivates reverence. The Lord&apos;s Supper is the NT&apos;s covenant meal before the Lord — not for the formation of fear but of gratitude, remembrance, and union: &quot;For as often as you eat this bread and drink the cup, you proclaim the Lord&apos;s death until he comes&quot; (1 Cor 11:26). The feast in YHWH&apos;s presence becomes the feast in Christ&apos;s presence. Theme.</p>",
"24": "<p>If the journey to the sanctuary is too long, convert the tithe to money. The covenant&apos;s practical accommodation to distance — the principle of tithing is preserved even when the original form is impossible. The NT extends this pragmatic flexibility in maintaining the giving principle: Paul&apos;s collection for the Jerusalem church (2 Cor 8–9) is the covenant community caring for one another across geographic distances, the tithing principle operating through new channels. Theme.</p>",
"25": "<p>Convert the tithe to money and take it to the place the LORD will choose. The flexibility of the covenant&apos;s economic provisions reflects the God who works within human conditions. In Christ, the entire economy of covenant giving is transformed from obligation to overflow: &quot;we have received grace upon grace&quot; (John 1:16); &quot;give, and it will be given to you&quot; (Luke 6:38). The tithe-to-money conversion is a small sign of the covenant&apos;s ongoing adaptation to life&apos;s realities. Revelation of God.</p>",
"26": "<p>&quot;Spend the money for whatever you desire... and eat there before the LORD your God and rejoice, you and your household.&quot; The tithe feast is genuinely festive — the worshipper chooses freely and rejoices. The tithe is not joyless obligation; it culminates in a celebration before YHWH that includes the worshipper&apos;s own pleasure. In Christ, the feast-motif culminates in the eschatological wedding banquet: &quot;Blessed are those who are invited to the marriage supper of the Lamb&quot; (Rev 19:9). The tithe feast&apos;s joy is a foretaste of the ultimate celebration. Theme.</p>",
"27": "<p>&quot;Do not neglect the Levite who lives in your towns, for he has no portion or inheritance among you.&quot; The Levite — landless by divine design, sustained by covenant provision — must not be forgotten in the celebration. The principle of caring for those whose calling precludes conventional income continues in the NT: &quot;Let the elders who rule well be considered worthy of double honor, especially those who labor in preaching and teaching&quot; (1 Tim 5:17). The pattern of sustaining those who minister the covenant community is rooted in the Levitical system. Theme.</p>",
"28": "<p>Every third year the tithe stays in the local towns for distribution. The triennial tithe as a systematic local welfare mechanism — not brought to the central sanctuary but kept nearby for the Levite, foreigner, fatherless, and widow. The early church&apos;s daily distribution of food (Acts 6:1), care for widows (1 Tim 5:3–16), and Paul&apos;s collection for the poor (Rom 15:26–27) are the NT expressions of this covenant welfare principle. Theme.</p>",
"29": "<p>&quot;So that the Levite... and the resident foreigner, the fatherless, and the widow... may come and eat and be satisfied. Then the LORD your God will bless you in all the work of your hands.&quot; Generosity to the vulnerable brings YHWH&apos;s blessing. Jesus&apos; teaching that care for &quot;the least of these&quot; is service to him (Matt 25:40) and the early church&apos;s communal care echo this covenant mechanism. In Christ, the blessing that follows covenant generosity has its ultimate source: &quot;He who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all, how will he not also with him graciously give us all things?&quot; (Rom 8:32). Revelation of God.</p>"
},
"15": {
"1": "<p>The sabbatical year — release every seventh year. The shĕmiṭṭâ extends the Sabbath pattern into economics: debt is released, the land rests, creation breathes. Jesus&apos; proclamation of &quot;the year of the LORD&apos;s favor&quot; in Luke 4:18–19 (citing Isa 61:1–2, which itself draws on the Jubilee/sabbatical-year legislation) announces the ultimate release — not agricultural debt but the deeper bondage of sin and death. The sabbatical year is the shadow; Christ&apos;s proclamation of liberation is the substance. Shadow.</p>",
"2": "<p>Creditors must cancel debts to fellow Israelites — the LORD&apos;s release is proclaimed. The mutual release of debt within the covenant community creates a social ecology of grace. Jesus builds the same logic into the Lord&apos;s Prayer: &quot;Forgive us our debts, as we also have forgiven our debtors&quot; (Matt 6:12). The reception of God&apos;s forgiveness creates the capacity and obligation to extend forgiveness to others. The sabbatical-year debt release is the economic form of what Christ gives as spiritual reality. Theme.</p>",
"3": "<p>Debts may be collected from foreigners but must be released for fellow Israelites. The covenant community operates under a distinctive economy of grace. In Christ, the community of forgiven-forgivers expands beyond ethnic Israel to include all who are in him: &quot;Bear with each other and forgive one another if any of you has a grievance against someone. Forgive as the Lord forgave you&quot; (Col 3:13). The internal economy of grace that once defined the covenant people now defines the church. Theme.</p>",
"4": "<p>&quot;There need be no poor among you.&quot; The vision of a community without poverty — contingent on covenant obedience. The early church realizes this vision through the Spirit: &quot;there was not a needy person among them, for as many as were owners of lands or houses sold them&quot; (Acts 4:34 — echoing Deut 15:4 directly). Luke&apos;s explicit echo of Deuteronomy&apos;s language in Acts marks the church as the community where the covenant vision becomes reality through Christ and the Spirit. Direct NT echo (Acts 4:34).</p>",
"5": "<p>&quot;If only you carefully obey the voice of the LORD your God.&quot; The covenant vision is conditioned on obedience the law cannot guarantee. The &quot;if only&quot; signals the law&apos;s own limitation — it states the condition it cannot itself fulfill. In Christ, this condition is met: he perfectly obeyed, and through the Spirit he empowers his people&apos;s obedience. &quot;For God has done what the law, weakened by the flesh, could not do&quot; (Rom 8:3–4). The law&apos;s conditional vision becomes the Spirit&apos;s accomplished reality. Theme.</p>",
"6": "<p>&quot;The LORD your God will bless you as he has promised, and you will lend to many nations but not borrow.&quot; The economic blessing of covenant faithfulness flows to the nations — Israel as the lender rather than the borrower. In Christ, the spiritual blessing flows to the nations: the church is entrusted with the gospel of grace to lend to the whole world — &quot;a light for the Gentiles, that you may bring salvation to the ends of the earth&quot; (Acts 13:47, citing Isa 49:6). The covenant blessing moves from the economic to the spiritual register. Theme.</p>",
"7": "<p>&quot;You shall not harden your heart or shut your hand against your poor brother. Instead, you shall open your hand wide.&quot; The open hand as the sign of the covenant community. This language recurs in Jesus&apos; teaching: &quot;Give to the one who begs from you, and do not refuse the one who would borrow from you&quot; (Matt 5:42). James connects the shut hand directly to dead faith (Jas 2:15–17). The hardened heart toward the poor is the covenant violation that the law condemns and Christ exposes. Theme.</p>",
"8": "<p>&quot;You shall open your hand wide to him and lend him whatever he needs, enough for his lack.&quot; The open hand gives generously, enough for the actual need — not a token gesture but sufficient provision. In Christ, the sufficient provision is defined at its highest: &quot;And my God will supply every need of yours according to his riches in glory in Christ Jesus&quot; (Phil 4:19). The covenant pattern of sufficient provision mirrors the divine character. Revelation of God.</p>",
"9": "<p>&quot;Guard against an unworthy thought in your heart: &apos;The seventh year, the year of release, is near.&apos;&quot; The law must guard against the calculating refusal of generosity. The Deuteronomic warning anticipates the heart&apos;s capacity to weaponize the law — to use the approaching release year as a reason to withhold rather than to give. Jesus addresses this same heart dynamic: &quot;when you give to the needy, do not let your left hand know what your right hand is doing&quot; (Matt 6:3). The calculating heart that Deuteronomy warns against is the same the Sermon on the Mount addresses. Theme.</p>",
"10": "<p>&quot;Give to him generously, and do not be reluctant when you give, for because of this the LORD your God will bless you in all your work.&quot; Generous giving, without inner reluctance, brings divine blessing. Paul applies the same principle: &quot;Whoever sows sparingly will also reap sparingly, and whoever sows bountifully will also reap bountifully... God loves a cheerful giver&quot; (2 Cor 9:6–7). The Deuteronomic link between generous giving and divine blessing is the OT foundation for Paul&apos;s theology of generosity. Theme.</p>",
"11": "<p>&quot;For there will never cease to be poor people in the land. That is why I am commanding you to open your hand wide to your brother.&quot; Jesus directly quotes this verse when defending the woman who anoints him: &quot;For you always have the poor with you, but you will not always have me&quot; (Matt 26:11; Mark 14:7; John 12:8). The Deuteronomic statement becomes the context for understanding the unrepeatable nature of Christ&apos;s presence — the poor are always with us and always deserve care; Christ was uniquely present for a finite period. Direct NT citation.</p>",
"12": "<p>The Hebrew slave released in the seventh year. The slave-release law extends the sabbatical principle to persons — freedom granted at the seventh year, mirroring the debt release of vv.1–2. Paul uses the slave-freedom language christologically: &quot;For freedom Christ has set us free; stand firm therefore, and do not submit again to a yoke of slavery&quot; (Gal 5:1). The seventh-year release from indentured service is the type; Christ&apos;s liberation from sin&apos;s slavery is the substance. Shadow.</p>",
"13": "<p>&quot;When you set him free, you shall not send him away empty-handed.&quot; The freed slave goes out with generous provision — not returned to the vulnerability of poverty. In Christ, those set free are sent out with every provision: &quot;His divine power has given us everything we need for a godly life&quot; (2 Pet 1:3). Freedom in Christ is not a bare release but a release into abundance. Revelation of God.</p>",
"14": "<p>&quot;Supply him generously from your flock, your threshing floor, and your winepress. Give to him as the LORD your God has blessed you.&quot; The provision for the freed slave mirrors the scale of God&apos;s blessing — give proportionally to what you have received. The principle of proportional generosity grounded in divine blessing is the OT basis for Paul&apos;s theology: &quot;He who supplies seed to the sower and bread for food will supply and multiply your seed for sowing and increase the harvest of your righteousness&quot; (2 Cor 9:10). Theme.</p>",
"15": "<p>&quot;Remember that you were a slave in Egypt, and the LORD your God redeemed you.&quot; Memory of redemption grounds ethical action — the redeemed must be redemptive toward others. The NT extends this logic to Christ&apos;s redemption: &quot;knowing that you were ransomed... with the precious blood of Christ&quot; (1 Pet 1:18–19) shapes every ethical obligation. The memory of redemption creates the character of the redeemed. Theme.</p>",
"16": "<p>The voluntary permanent servant — who loves his master and chooses not to leave — has his ear pierced against the door. This is the voluntary, love-motivated covenant bond. Psalm 40:6 (&quot;ears you have dug for me; you did not desire burnt offering and sin offering. Then I said, &apos;Here I am; I have come&apos;&quot;) is cited in Hebrews 10:5–7 as the words of Christ at the Incarnation: &quot;a body you have prepared for me... I have come to do your will, O God.&quot; The willing servant who chooses permanent bondage out of love for his master is the type Christ embodies at the Incarnation. Direct type (Heb 10:5–7).</p>",
"17": "<p>The awl through the ear against the door — a permanent mark of voluntary covenant servitude. The ear piercing enacts permanent, public, irrevocable commitment. Christ&apos;s commitment to the Father&apos;s will is irrevocable and public: &quot;he humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death, even death on a cross&quot; (Phil 2:8). What the ear-piercing marked for the slave, the cross marked for the Son — permanent, visible, irreversible covenant loyalty. Type.</p>",
"18": "<p>&quot;Do not find it difficult when you set him free, for he has served you six years at half the cost of a hired worker.&quot; The law removes the economic complaint against generosity in freedom-giving. The releasing master is to set the slave free without resentment. God sets free without resentment — at infinite cost, through the cross: &quot;God was reconciling the world to himself in Christ, not counting people&apos;s sins against them&quot; (2 Cor 5:19). The freedom given freely and without reluctance reaches its fullest expression in the cross. Revelation of God.</p>",
"19": "<p>&quot;You shall set apart for the LORD your God every firstborn male born of your herd and your flock.&quot; The firstborn male consecrated to YHWH — the first and best dedicated as representative of the whole. Christ is the firstborn in every sense the NT deploys: &quot;the firstborn of all creation&quot; (Col 1:15); &quot;the firstborn among many brothers&quot; (Rom 8:29); &quot;the firstborn from the dead&quot; (Col 1:18; Rev 1:5). The firstborn male dedicated to YHWH is the type; Christ as YHWH&apos;s consecrated firstborn who gives himself as the definitive offering is the fulfillment. Direct type.</p>",
"20": "<p>The firstborn animal is eaten before the LORD at the central sanctuary — the firstborn offering becomes a covenant feast. The firstborn&apos;s dedication and the covenant meal are linked. In Christ, the one who is the firstborn from the dead (Col 1:18) is also the host of the covenant meal: &quot;I will not drink again of this fruit of the vine until that day when I drink it new with you in my Father&apos;s kingdom&quot; (Matt 26:29). The firstborn meal anticipates the eschatological feast where Christ himself is both offering and host. Type.</p>",
"21": "<p>&quot;But if it has any defect — if it is lame or blind or has any serious flaw — you do not sacrifice it to the LORD your God.&quot; The defect-free requirement is absolute — the sacrifice presented to YHWH must be unblemished. Christ qualifies where every other candidate is disqualified: &quot;a lamb without blemish or spot&quot; (1 Pet 1:19); &quot;through the eternal Spirit offered himself without blemish to God&quot; (Heb 9:14). The law that disqualifies every defective offering positively requires the one perfect offering that Christ provides. Direct type.</p>",
"22": "<p>Defective firstborns may be eaten locally by anyone, clean or unclean alike — like a gazelle or deer. The animal that cannot be offered in the sanctuary is still good for food; it is not wasted. The distinction between the sacred and the common does not make the common worthless. In Christ, the entire creation is redeemed for God&apos;s glory: &quot;everything created by God is good, and nothing is to be rejected if it is received with thanksgiving&quot; (1 Tim 4:4). Revelation of God.</p>",
"23": "<p>&quot;Only do not eat its blood; pour it out on the ground like water.&quot; The blood prohibition maintains the sanctity of life — blood is life, and life belongs to YHWH. This ground-level prohibition prepares for the central importance of blood in the covenant&apos;s sacrificial system and in Christ&apos;s atoning work. &quot;Without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness of sins&quot; (Heb 9:22) — the blood that Israel poured on the ground in reverence is the type of the blood Christ shed for the forgiveness that the whole sacrificial system anticipated. Type.</p>"
},
"16": {
"1": "<p>Observe the month of Abib and celebrate the Passover — &quot;for in the month of Abib the LORD your God brought you out of Egypt by night.&quot; The Passover feast commands annual re-enactment of the foundational redemption. Paul declares the Christological fulfillment: &quot;Christ, our Passover lamb, has been sacrificed&quot; (1 Cor 5:7). Jesus eats the Passover with his disciples and transforms it into the Lord&apos;s Supper (Luke 22:14–20), the meal that re-enacts not the Exodus from Egypt but the greater exodus of death and resurrection. Direct type.</p>",
"2": "<p>&quot;You shall sacrifice the Passover offering to the LORD your God — from the flock or the herd.&quot; The Passover offering from the flock is the lamb; the lamb is the symbol that runs through the entire biblical witness to Christ: John the Baptist (&quot;Behold, the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world&quot;, John 1:29), Paul (1 Cor 5:7), Peter (1 Pet 1:19), and Revelation (the Lamb on the throne, Rev 5:6). The Passover lamb commanded in Deuteronomy is the type whose sacrifice defines the whole. Direct type.</p>",
"3": "<p>&quot;For seven days you shall eat unleavened bread — the bread of affliction — because you left Egypt in haste.&quot; The unleavened bread is the bread of urgency and affliction — the opposite of the leisured leavened bread of ordinary life. Paul extends the unleavened-bread metaphor directly: &quot;Cleanse out the old leaven that you may be a new lump, as you really are unleavened. For Christ, our Passover lamb, has been sacrificed. Let us therefore celebrate the festival, not with the old leaven... but with the unleavened bread of sincerity and truth&quot; (1 Cor 5:7–8). Direct NT citation.</p>",
"4": "<p>&quot;None of the flesh you sacrifice on the evening of the first day shall remain until morning.&quot; The Passover lamb is fully consumed; nothing is left to decay. The Passover regulations anticipate Christ&apos;s body: &quot;not a bone of him shall be broken&quot; (John 19:36, citing Exod 12:46) — the regulations about the Passover lamb are fulfilled in the manner of Christ&apos;s death. And his body does not decay (Acts 2:31, citing Ps 16:10 — &quot;nor will you let your Holy One see corruption&quot;). Direct type.</p>",
"5": "<p>The Passover may not be sacrificed in just any town — only at the central sanctuary. The centralization of the Passover sacrifice at the one place YHWH chooses. In fulfillment: Jesus is crucified in Jerusalem, the central sanctuary city, during the Passover feast. John&apos;s Gospel especially emphasizes the temporal and geographic precision (John 18:28; 19:14, 31) — the Passover lamb is slain in exactly the place and at exactly the time the law required. Direct fulfillment.</p>",
"6": "<p>&quot;In the evening, at sunset, at the very time you came out of Egypt.&quot; The Passover sacrifice must occur at the specific time of the original Exodus. The sacrifice is temporally tethered to its founding event. Jesus is crucified during the Passover, as the Passover lambs are being slaughtered in the temple (John 19:14 notes it is &quot;about noon on the day of Preparation for the Passover&quot; — the afternoon when lambs were slaughtered). The typological precision is exact. Direct fulfillment.</p>",
"7": "<p>&quot;Cook and eat it at the place the LORD your God will choose, and in the morning you shall return to your tents.&quot; The Passover meal eaten at the central sanctuary, then return to ordinary life. The morning after the Passover sacrifice is the morning of freedom — the original Exodus began in the morning after the night of the angel of death. In Christ&apos;s Passover, the morning after is Easter morning — &quot;On the first day of the week, at early dawn, they went to the tomb&quot; (Luke 24:1). The Passover morning becomes the resurrection morning. Type.</p>",
"8": "<p>&quot;On the seventh day there shall be a solemn assembly for the LORD your God — you shall do no work on that day.&quot; The seventh day closes the Passover week with a Sabbath assembly. The Sabbath-rest structure of the feast week points toward the eschatological rest that Christ inaugurates. Hebrews 4:9–10 — &quot;there remains a Sabbath rest for the people of God, for whoever has entered God&apos;s rest has also rested from his works as God did from his&quot; — is the Christological fulfillment of the Sabbath assembly that closes the Passover week. Theme.</p>",
"9": "<p>&quot;Count off seven weeks from when the sickle is first put to the standing grain.&quot; The Feast of Weeks (Shavuot/Pentecost) begins with the barley harvest and is counted from Passover. The Spirit is poured out on the church at Pentecost (Acts 2:1–4) — the Feast of Weeks, the harvest festival. The Spirit is the firstfruits of the eschatological harvest (Rom 8:23). The harvest-timing of the Feast of Weeks is the shadow; Pentecost as the harvest of the Spirit&apos;s first fruits is the fulfillment. Direct fulfillment (Acts 2).</p>",
"10": "<p>&quot;Celebrate the Feast of Weeks to the LORD your God with a freewill offering — give in proportion to how the LORD your God has blessed you.&quot; The Feast of Weeks is a freewill offering feast — proportional, generous, responsive to blessing. In Acts 2, the Spirit poured out at Pentecost produces exactly this generosity: &quot;All who believed were together and had all things in common. And they were selling their possessions and belongings and distributing the proceeds to all&quot; (Acts 2:44–45). The freewill-offering feast becomes the Spirit-generated generosity of the community. Type.</p>",
"11": "<p>&quot;You shall rejoice before the LORD your God — you, your son and daughter, your servants, the Levite, the sojourner, the fatherless, and the widow.&quot; The Feast of Weeks is comprehensively inclusive — the social hierarchy is irrelevant in the joy before YHWH. In Christ, this inclusivity is radicalized: &quot;There is neither Jew nor Greek, there is neither slave nor free, there is no male and female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus&quot; (Gal 3:28). The feast-inclusion of the vulnerable and the foreigner becomes, in Christ, the abolition of every division. Theme.</p>",
"12": "<p>&quot;Remember that you were a slave in Egypt, and be careful to observe these statutes.&quot; Memory of slavery grounds festival observance — the feast is joyful precisely because slavery is over. In the Lord&apos;s Supper, the memory of spiritual slavery — &quot;do this in remembrance of me&quot; (Luke 22:19) — grounds the eucharistic joy. The freed slave&apos;s feast and the redeemed sinner&apos;s eucharist share the same logic: joy rooted in remembered deliverance. Theme.</p>",
"13": "<p>The Feast of Booths (Sukkot) — seven days at the final harvest, when all the produce has been gathered. Sukkot is the feast that commemorates Israel&apos;s wilderness dwelling in booths. Jesus is in Jerusalem for the Feast of Booths in John 7–8 — the backdrop for his most explicit claims about himself as the source of living water (John 7:37–38) and as the light of the world (John 8:12). His presence at Sukkot activates the feast&apos;s imagery: he is what the water-pouring ceremony and the lamp-lighting ceremony at Sukkot pointed toward. Shadow.</p>",
"14": "<p>Rejoice at the Feast of Booths — all of you together, including servants, Levites, sojourners, fatherless, and widows. The comprehensive joy of Sukkot. Zechariah 14:16 envisions all nations coming up to Jerusalem to celebrate the Feast of Booths in the messianic age — the feast that was once Israel&apos;s becomes the feast of all nations. In Christ, the eschatological Sukkot begins: &quot;Salvation belongs to our God who sits on the throne, and to the Lamb!&quot; (Rev 7:10) — the great multitude from all nations celebrates the ultimate harvest feast. Theme.</p>",
"15": "<p>&quot;The LORD your God will bless you in all your produce and in all the work of your hands; and you shall be completely joyful.&quot; Complete joy — the fullness of covenant blessing expressed as total festive delight. Jesus promises this same fullness: &quot;I have said these things to you, that my joy may be in you, and that your joy may be full&quot; (John 15:11). The complete joy of Sukkot is the OT anticipation of the fullness of joy that Christ gives. Theme.</p>",
"16": "<p>&quot;Three times a year all your males shall appear before the LORD your God at the place he will choose: at the Feast of Unleavened Bread, at the Feast of Weeks, and at the Feast of Booths.&quot; The three pilgrimage feasts as the covenant calendar&apos;s framework. All three are Christologically fulfilled: Passover/Unleavened Bread in Christ&apos;s death and resurrection, the Feast of Weeks/Pentecost in the Spirit&apos;s outpouring, and the Feast of Booths in Christ&apos;s tabernacling with his people (John 1:14 — &quot;the Word became flesh and tabernacled among us,&quot; ἐσκήνωσεν). The entire covenant calendar finds its fulfillment in Christ. Theme becoming fulfillment.</p>",
"17": "<p>&quot;Every man shall give as he is able, in proportion to the blessing the LORD your God has given him.&quot; Giving proportional to received blessing — the festival offering is calibrated to what YHWH has done. In Christ, the measure of giving is redefined by the measure of God&apos;s giving: &quot;For you know the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ, that though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor, so that you by his poverty might become rich&quot; (2 Cor 8:9). The standard of proportional giving is set by the cross. Revelation of God.</p>",
"18": "<p>&quot;You shall appoint judges and officials throughout all your towns... and they shall judge the people with just decisions.&quot; The covenant community requires just judgment at every level. Christ as the just judge fulfills what the covenant&apos;s judicial system could only approximate: &quot;the Father... has given all judgment to the Son&quot; (John 5:22); &quot;he has fixed a day on which he will judge the world in righteousness by a man whom he has appointed&quot; (Acts 17:31). The local judges are the shadow; the universal Judge is Christ. Shadow.</p>",
"19": "<p>&quot;Do not pervert justice; do not show favoritism; do not accept a bribe — for a bribe blinds the eyes of the wise and twists the words of the innocent.&quot; Three prohibitions that protect the innocent. Judas&apos; acceptance of thirty pieces of silver (Matt 26:14–16) is the precise inversion: a bribe accepted to twist the words and destroy the innocent one. The judicial standard of Deuteronomy is violated in the very act that fulfills the Passover type — the condemnation of the one perfectly innocent man becomes the sacrifice that atones. Theme/irony.</p>",
"20": "<p>&quot;Justice, and justice alone, you shall pursue — so that you may live and possess the land.&quot; The double emphasis on justice — ṣeḏeq ṣeḏeq — the repetition signaling absolute commitment. In Christ, divine justice and divine mercy meet at the cross: &quot;God presented Christ as a propitiation through faith in his blood... to demonstrate his righteousness... so that he would be just and the one who justifies those who have faith in Jesus&quot; (Rom 3:25–26). The justice pursued in Deuteronomy is realized in the cross. Revelation of God.</p>",
"21": "<p>&quot;You shall not set up any wooden Asherah pole beside the altar of the LORD your God.&quot; The prohibition of syncretism — YHWH&apos;s altar must not be mixed with Canaanite fertility symbols. The jealous exclusivity of YHWH&apos;s worship is the OT ground for Paul&apos;s: &quot;You cannot drink the cup of the Lord and the cup of demons. You cannot partake of the table of the Lord and the table of demons&quot; (1 Cor 10:21). In Christ, the exclusive devotion demanded here is the devotion to the one who is himself the way, the truth, and the life — no other pole alongside him. Theme.</p>",
"22": "<p>&quot;Do not erect a sacred stone pillar, for the LORD your God hates these.&quot; The maṣṣēḇâ (standing stone) was a Canaanite fertility symbol. YHWH&apos;s hatred of these idols is the expression of his exclusive claim on Israel&apos;s worship. In Christ, the exclusive claim is made in personal terms: &quot;No one comes to the Father except through me&quot; (John 14:6). The prohibition of substitute worship is fulfilled in the person who is himself the only legitimate approach to God. Revelation of God.</p>"
},
"17": {
"1": "<p>&quot;You shall not sacrifice to the LORD your God an ox or a sheep that has a defect, any serious flaw whatever — that is detestable to the LORD your God.&quot; The unblemished sacrifice requirement. The law requires what only Christ can provide: &quot;a lamb without blemish or spot&quot; (1 Pet 1:19); &quot;through the eternal Spirit offered himself without blemish to God&quot; (Heb 9:14). The absolute prohibition of the defective offering positively implies the perfect offering that the law itself cannot produce from within the fallen creation. Direct type.</p>",
"2": "<p>If a covenant-violator is found among you — someone who has done what is evil by transgressing the covenant. The covenant violation as the legal category. The irony of the trial of Jesus: the one who had never transgressed the covenant is processed through the covenant&apos;s legal procedure for covenant violators. The innocent one is tried as a transgressor — &quot;he was numbered with the transgressors&quot; (Isa 53:12; Luke 22:37). The legal category prepared for the guilty is the category in which the innocent one stands. Theme.</p>",
"3": "<p>Serving other gods and bowing to heavenly bodies — the specific apostasy. The covenant violation that receives the capital sentence is idolatry — transferring worship from YHWH to the created order. In Christ, the opposite of this apostasy is the confession that Jesus is Lord (Phil 2:11) — the transfer of ultimate allegiance from every created thing to the one who is both Creator and Redeemer. The apostasy Deuteronomy punishes is the failure Christ&apos;s Lordship reverses. Theme.</p>",
"4": "<p>&quot;You shall investigate diligently; and if it is true and confirmed that such a detestable thing has been done in Israel.&quot; Diligent investigation before the death sentence — no rush to execution. The standard of careful judicial procedure. Jesus&apos; trial violates this standard: no careful investigation, accusations inconsistent and false, the sentence driven by political expediency (John 11:50: &quot;it is better for you that one man die for the people&quot;). The judicial standard of Deuteronomy is abused in the condemnation of Christ. Theme/contrast.</p>",
"5": "<p>The covenant violator is brought to the town gate and stoned to death. The public execution at the gate. In Jesus&apos; case: the execution outside the city gate on a hill, publicly visible. Hebrews 13:12 draws out the significance: &quot;Jesus also suffered outside the city gate to make the people holy through his own blood&quot; — he died in the place of public execution as the covenant violator&apos;s substitute. Direct typological application (Heb 13:12).</p>",
"6": "<p>&quot;A person shall be put to death only on the testimony of two or three witnesses; no one is to be executed on the testimony of a single witness.&quot; The two-or-three-witness rule protects against judicial murder. Paul applies this rule directly for church discipline (2 Cor 13:1; 1 Tim 5:19). In the Sanhedrin trial, the false witnesses against Jesus could not agree (Mark 14:55–59), violating the very standard Deuteronomy requires. The innocent one is condemned in violation of the law designed to protect the innocent. Theme/contrast.</p>",
"7": "<p>&quot;The witnesses shall be first to put him to death, and then all the people shall follow.&quot; Witnesses bear primary responsibility for the execution. The covenant&apos;s judicial accountability mechanism: those who accuse must execute, owning the consequence of their testimony. In Christ&apos;s trial: the chief priests and elders drove the crowd to cry &quot;crucify him&quot; (Matt 27:20–22), and the Sanhedrin bore primary responsibility. Peter&apos;s Pentecost sermon addresses this directly: &quot;you killed the Author of life&quot; (Acts 3:15). Revelation of God&apos;s justice.</p>",
"8": "<p>Cases too difficult for local courts are brought to the central sanctuary — the Levitical priests and the judge give the final verdict. The judicial hierarchy culminates in the presence of YHWH at the sanctuary. In Christ, the supreme court is the heavenly throne where Christ sits at the Father&apos;s right hand: &quot;We must all appear before the judgment seat of Christ&quot; (2 Cor 5:10). The ascending levels of the Deuteronomic judiciary find their summit in the eschatological judgment seat of the one appointed to judge all things. Shadow.</p>",
"9": "<p>&quot;You shall go to the Levitical priests and to the judge who is serving at that time, and they shall give you the verdict.&quot; The high court&apos;s authority flows from YHWH&apos;s presence in the sanctuary. In Christ, access to the Father&apos;s authority is through the great High Priest: &quot;we have a great high priest who has ascended into heaven, Jesus the Son of God&quot; (Heb 4:14). The judge at the sanctuary is the type; Christ as the priest-judge at the heavenly sanctuary is the fulfillment. Type.</p>",
"10": "<p>&quot;You shall carry out the verdict they announce to you from that place the LORD will choose, and be careful to do all they instruct you.&quot; The supreme court&apos;s verdict is binding — obedience to the highest covenant authority. In Christ, the binding verdict is the verdict of justification: &quot;Who shall bring any charge against God&apos;s elect? It is God who justifies. Who is to condemn? Christ Jesus is the one who died — more than that, who was raised — who is at the right hand of God, who indeed is interceding for us&quot; (Rom 8:33–34). Revelation of God.</p>",
"11": "<p>&quot;According to the instruction they give you and the verdict they pronounce, you shall act. Do not deviate from what they declare to you — neither to the right nor to the left.&quot; The covenant community must submit to the appointed court&apos;s judgment. In Christ, the submission to divine authority is the posture of the one who &quot;did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped, but emptied himself... and became obedient to the point of death&quot; (Phil 2:6–8). The obedience to the supreme court that Deuteronomy commands is modeled perfectly by Christ in his submission to the Father. Theme.</p>",
"12": "<p>&quot;The man who acts arrogantly by refusing to obey the priest who stands to minister before the LORD your God, or the judge — that man shall die.&quot; Presumptuous disregard for the supreme covenant authority is capital. Hebrews 10:28–29 explicitly applies this logic to Christ&apos;s superior authority: &quot;Anyone who rejected the law of Moses died without mercy on the testimony of two or three witnesses. How much worse punishment, do you think, will be deserved by the one who has trampled underfoot the Son of God?&quot; The escalation of authority from Moses to Christ escalates the consequence of rejection. Direct NT application (Heb 10:28–29).</p>",
"13": "<p>&quot;All the people shall hear and be afraid, and they will not act presumptuously again.&quot; The deterrent function of public justice — the fear of God begins with the fear of divine judgment. In Christ, the cross is the supreme demonstration of the cost of sin: &quot;He who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all&quot; (Rom 8:32) — at the cross, the presumptuous disregard for God&apos;s authority is met by the most costly imaginable response. The cross both deters and provides escape. Revelation of God.</p>",
"14": "<p>&quot;When you come to the land... and you say, &apos;I want to set a king over me, like all the nations around me,&apos;&quot; — the law anticipates the monarchy before it exists. The permission and regulation of kingship sets up the entire Davidic covenant narrative. The king YHWH chooses is ultimately Christ, the son of David (Matt 1:1; Acts 2:30–36): God says to him, &quot;You are my Son; today I have begotten you&quot; (Ps 2:7, cited in Acts 13:33; Heb 1:5; 5:5) — the chosen king of Deuteronomy&apos;s provision is appointed by divine declaration. Direct type.</p>",
"15": "<p>&quot;You may set a king over you — but he must be the one the LORD your God chooses... one from among your brothers.&quot; Two requirements: divine choice and brotherhood with the covenant community. Christ satisfies both: chosen by the Father (&quot;This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased&quot;, Matt 3:17) and truly one of his brothers (&quot;he is not ashamed to call them brothers&quot;, Heb 2:11; &quot;born of woman, born under the law&quot;, Gal 4:4). The king from among the brothers, appointed by YHWH, is exactly who Jesus is. Direct type.</p>",
"16": "<p>The king must not multiply horses or return to Egypt. The anti-accumulation provision for the king — no military self-sufficiency through cavalry power. Zechariah 9:9–10 fulfills this: the messianic king comes &quot;humble, and mounted on a donkey&quot; rather than a war horse, and &quot;he will cut off the chariot from Ephraim and the war horse from Jerusalem.&quot; Jesus enters Jerusalem on a donkey (Matt 21:5; John 12:15) — the direct fulfillment of the Zechariah prophecy that itself fulfills the Deuteronomic anti-horse provision. Direct fulfillment (Zech 9:9 citing Deut 17:16, fulfilled in Matt 21:5).</p>",
"17": "<p>The king must not multiply wives (lest his heart be led astray) or accumulate excessive silver and gold. Solomon violated all three provisions (1 Kgs 10–11). Christ fulfills the negative provisions: no accumulation of wives, no hoarded wealth (&quot;foxes have holes... but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head,&quot; Matt 8:20), no military force. The king who perfectly embodies the covenant law of the king is the one who comes in poverty, celibacy, and nonviolent authority. Type fulfilled in contrast to Solomon.</p>",
"18": "<p>&quot;When he takes the throne of his kingdom, he shall write for himself in a book a copy of this law, verified by the Levitical priests.&quot; The Torah-immersed king — the law is not external to him but personally written, carried, and read. Psalm 1, which opens the Psalter, describes the blessed person who meditates on the law day and night — a description the NT reads in relation to Christ as the one in whom Torah-meditation is perfectly realized. Christ is not merely a student of the law but is himself the living Word who is its source (John 1:1; Matt 5:17). Shadow.</p>",
"19": "<p>&quot;It shall be with him, and he shall read in it all the days of his life, that he may learn to fear the LORD his God by keeping all the words of this law and these statutes and doing them.&quot; The king who reads the Torah daily and keeps all its words. Christ is this king: he keeps every word of the law without exception, teaches it with his own authority (&quot;You have heard that it was said... but I say to you,&quot; Matt 5:21–48), and fulfills it from within (&quot;I have not come to abolish the Law or the Prophets but to fulfill them,&quot; Matt 5:17). The Torah-keeping king of Deuteronomy is Jesus. Direct type.</p>",
"20": "<p>&quot;So that his heart will not be lifted up above his brothers, and so that he will not turn from the commandment to the right or to the left — and thus he may reign long.&quot; The humble, covenant-keeping king who does not deviate from the commandment. Christ embodies this perfectly: &quot;he humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death, even death on a cross. Therefore God has highly exalted him and bestowed on him the name that is above every name&quot; (Phil 2:8–9). The humble, commandment-keeping king of Deuteronomy receives the exaltation that follows covenant obedience. His reign is not &quot;long&quot; — it is eternal. Direct type.</p>"
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'deuteronomy')
    merge_comm(existing, DEUTERONOMY)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'deuteronomy', existing)
    print('Deuteronomy 14-17 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
